# Maximum Ice Cream Bars (LeetCode 1833)

## 📌 Problem Statement

You are given:

* An array `costs` where `costs[i]` is the price of the `i-th` ice cream bar.
* An integer `coins` representing the number of coins you have.

You may buy ice cream bars in any order as long as you have enough coins.

Return the maximum number of ice cream bars you can buy.

---

## 🧠 Approach

### Counting Sort / Frequency Array

The constraints allow ice cream costs up to `100000`.

Instead of sorting the entire array (`O(n log n)`), we can use a frequency array to count how many bars exist for each cost.

### Key Idea

To maximize the number of bars purchased:

* Always buy the cheapest available ice cream first.
* Process costs in increasing order.
* For each cost `x`, buy as many bars as possible:

```text
buy = min(coins / x, frequency[x])
```

* Update:

  * Remaining coins
  * Total bars purchased

This effectively performs a counting-sort-style greedy purchase.

---

## 💻 Code (C++)

```cpp
constexpr int M = 1e5 + 1;
int freq[M];

class Solution {
public:
    static int maxIceCream(vector<int>& costs, int coins) {
        int xMax = 0;

        for (int x : costs) {
            freq[x]++;
            xMax = max(xMax, x);
        }

        int cnt = 0;

        for (int x = 1; x <= xMax; x++) {
            const int f = freq[x];

            if (f == 0)
                continue;

            int buy = min(coins / x, f);

            if (buy == 0)
                break;

            cnt += buy;
            coins -= buy * x;
        }

        // Reset frequency array for future test cases
        for (int x : costs)
            freq[x] = 0;

        return cnt;
    }
};

